# PHASE 2 — THE CLOUD COST AUDIT: FIND & ELIMINATE HIDDEN WASTE

## COMPLETE SRT — SERIES 2

1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,000
Welcome back to the course.

2
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:12,000
In Series one, you built the foundation.
You learned what FinOps is. You learned the three phases.

3
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:18,000
You learned unit economics. You built a tagging strategy.
You ran your first Cost Explorer queries.
You created your baseline document.

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:24,000
That was the warm-up. That was the setup.
That was you learning the rules of the game.

5
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:30,000
Now it's time to play.

6
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:36,000
Series two is where we stop talking about waste
and start finding it.

7
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:42,000
Series two is where we stop being theoretical
and start being practical.

8
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:48,000
Series two is where you transform from someone
who knows about FinOps into someone who actually does FinOps.

9
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:54,000
By the end of this series, you will have identified
actual dollar amounts of waste in your AWS account.

10
00:00:54,000 --> 01:00:00,000
Not estimated savings. Not projected savings.
Not hypothetical examples from a slide deck.

11
01:00:00,000 --> 01:06:00,000
Real waste. Real dollars. Real numbers from your account,
your resources, your bill.

12
01:06:00,000 --> 01:12:00,000
Let me tell you a story before we start.
Because stories stick. Stories help you remember why this matters.

13
01:12:00,000 --> 01:18:00,000
I once worked with a startup. Series A.
Forty employees. Growing fast.

14
01:18:00,000 --> 01:24:00,000
They had raised ten million dollars.
They were hiring. They were shipping.
They were doing all the things startups are supposed to do.

15
01:24:00,000 --> 01:30:00,000
But their AWS bill was growing faster than their revenue.
Forty-seven thousand dollars a month. And growing.

16
01:30:00,000 --> 01:36:00,000
Up and to the right. The kind of chart
that makes a CFO break into a cold sweat.

17
01:36:00,000 --> 01:42:00,000
They thought it was normal.
After all, they were processing millions of RAG queries.

18
01:42:00,000 --> 01:48:00,000
They had a large Kubernetes cluster.
They had multiple databases. They had data transfer costs.

19
01:48:00,000 --> 01:54:00,000
They were doing real work. Real work costs real money.

20
01:54:00,000 --> 02:00:00,000
But they had never done an audit.
They had never looked closely at the bill.

21
02:00:00,000 --> 02:06:00,000
They had never asked the question:
is this normal, or is this waste?

22
02:06:00,000 --> 02:12:00,000
I ran the audit. The same audit you are about to run.
Here is what I found.

23
02:12:00,000 --> 02:18:00,000
Forty percent of their EC2 instances were at least twice
as large as they needed to be.

24
02:18:00,000 --> 02:24:00,000
They had selected large instance types at launch, two years ago,
and never revisited the decision.

25
02:24:00,000 --> 02:30:00,000
The workload hadn't grown. The instances hadn't changed.
But they were still paying for the large ones.

26
02:30:00,000 --> 02:36:00,000
Monthly waste from overprovisioned EC2: eight thousand dollars.

27
02:36:00,000 --> 02:42:00,000
They had twelve unattached Elastic IPs.
Twelve. Each one costing three dollars and sixty-five cents a month.

28
02:42:00,000 --> 02:48:00,000
Doing absolutely nothing. Just sitting there in the account.
Reserved, allocated, but not attached to any instance.

29
02:48:00,000 --> 02:54:00,000
Monthly waste: forty-three dollars and eighty cents.
Not huge. But symbolic.

30
02:54:00,000 --> 03:00:00,000
If they were wasting money on something this obvious,
what else were they wasting money on?

31
03:00:00,000 --> 03:06:00,000
All of their EBS volumes were gp2. Every single one.
Hundreds of volumes. None of them had been migrated to gp3.

32
03:06:00,000 --> 03:12:00,000
Gp2 costs ten cents per gigabyte per month.
Gp3 costs eight cents per gigabyte per month.

33
03:12:00,000 --> 03:18:00,000
Same performance. Same IOPS baseline.
Twenty percent cheaper. For zero work. For one command.

34
03:18:00,000 --> 03:24:00,000
Monthly waste: twelve hundred dollars.

35
03:24:00,000 --> 03:30:00,000
NAT Gateway was their fourth largest service.
They were sending all their S3 traffic through NAT Gateway.

36
03:30:00,000 --> 03:36:00,000
S3 traffic through NAT Gateway costs four point five cents per gigabyte.
S3 traffic through VPC Endpoints is completely free.

37
03:36:00,000 --> 03:42:00,000
They were paying for something that could be free.
Monthly waste: twenty-one hundred dollars.

38
03:42:00,000 --> 03:48:00,000
S3 had no lifecycle policies. None.
They had fifteen terabytes of old data
that hadn't been accessed in over a year.

39
03:48:00,000 --> 03:54:00,000
Some of it was three years old. Some of it was five years old.
All of it was in standard storage at two point three cents per gigabyte.

40
03:54:00,000 --> 04:00:00,000
It should have been in Glacier at zero point four cents per gigabyte.
That's eighty percent cheaper.

41
04:00:00,000 --> 04:06:00,000
Monthly waste from missing lifecycle policies: nine hundred dollars.

42
04:06:00,000 --> 04:12:00,000
Total identified waste from the audit:
twelve thousand two hundred forty-three dollars and eighty cents per month.

43
04:12:00,000 --> 04:18:00,000
Twenty-six percent of their bill.
Just from the audit. Just from looking.

44
04:18:00,000 --> 04:24:00,000
Just from running the commands you are about to run.

45
04:24:00,000 --> 04:30:00,000
No optimization yet. No rightsizing yet.
No Karpenter yet. No Spot instances yet. No Savings Plans yet.

46
04:30:00,000 --> 04:36:00,000
Just finding the obvious waste.
The low-hanging fruit.
The stuff that should never have been there in the first place.

47
04:36:00,000 --> 04:42:00,000
After implementing the fixes from Series two,
their bill dropped to thirty-four thousand eight hundred dollars.

48
04:42:00,000 --> 04:48:00,000
They saved twelve thousand two hundred forty-three dollars
in the first month.

49
04:48:00,000 --> 04:54:00,000
That's a hundred forty-six thousand dollars a year.

50
04:54:00,000 --> 05:00:00,000
For a Series A startup with forty employees,
that's a real person. That's a hire.

51
05:00:00,000 --> 05:06:00,000
That's a marketing budget. That's a sales team.
That's the difference between making payroll and not.

52
05:06:00,000 --> 05:12:00,000
And here is the best part.
The fixes took less than a day.

53
05:12:00,000 --> 05:18:00,000
A single day of work. Eight hours. One person.
Running commands. Saving a hundred forty-six thousand dollars a year.

54
05:18:00,000 --> 05:24:00,000
That's a return on investment of forty thousand percent.

55
05:24:00,000 --> 05:30:00,000
That's what Series two delivers.

56
05:30:00,000 --> 05:36:00,000
Now let me show you how to do it.

57
05:36:00,000 --> 05:42:00,000
Before we run any commands, let me remind you
about the environment variables we set in Series one.

58
05:42:00,000 --> 05:48:00,000
You need these for every command in this course.
Every single command uses them.

59
05:48:00,000 --> 05:54:00,000
If they're not set, the commands will fail.
If they're set incorrectly, the commands will give you wrong data.

60
05:54:00,000 --> 06:00:00,000
So let's set them again. Even if you set them in Series one.
Even if you think they're still set. Set them again.

61
06:00:00,000 --> 06:06:00,000
It takes five seconds. It saves twenty minutes of debugging.

62
06:06:00,000 --> 06:12:00,000
Here are the commands.

63
06:12:00,000 --> 06:18:00,000
export ACCOUNT_ID equals aws sts get-caller-identity
with query Account output text.

64
06:18:00,000 --> 06:24:00,000
export REGION equals us-east-1, or your preferred region.
export START equals date dash d 30 days ago plus YYYY-MM-DD.

65
06:24:00,000 --> 06:30:00,000
export END equals date plus YYYY-MM-DD.

66
06:30:00,000 --> 06:36:00,000
Important note for macOS users.
The date command on macOS is different.

67
06:36:00,000 --> 06:42:00,000
Instead of date dash d 30 days ago,
use date dash v dash 30d.

68
06:42:00,000 --> 06:48:00,000
Now verify that they're set correctly.
Run echo for each variable.

69
06:48:00,000 --> 06:54:00,000
echo dollar sign ACCOUNT_ID.
echo dollar sign REGION.
echo dollar sign START.
echo dollar sign END.

70
06:54:00,000 --> 07:00:00,000
You should see your twelve-digit account ID.
You should see us-east-1 or whatever region you chose.

71
07:00:00,000 --> 07:06:00,000
You should see a date that is thirty days ago.
You should see today's date.

72
07:06:00,000 --> 07:12:00,000
If any of these are empty, go back and run the export commands again.
Make sure you copied them exactly.

73
07:12:00,000 --> 07:18:00,000
Make sure there are no typos.
Make sure you didn't forget the dollar sign
or the parentheses or the quotes.

74
07:18:00,000 --> 07:24:00,000
Now verify that Cost Explorer is accessible.
This is the same command from Series one.

75
07:24:00,000 --> 07:30:00,000
It returns your total monthly spend.

76
07:30:00,000 --> 07:36:00,000
aws ce get-cost-and-usage with time period Start END,
granularity MONTHLY, metrics BlendedCost, query amount, output text.

77
07:36:00,000 --> 07:42:00,000
You should see a number. It might be zero if your account is new.
It might be a small number if you're just testing.

78
07:42:00,000 --> 07:48:00,000
It might be a large number if you're in production.
Whatever it is, write it down.

79
07:48:00,000 --> 07:54:00,000
This is your baseline. This is the number
you're going to reduce over the next ten series.

80
07:54:00,000 --> 08:00:00,000
If you get an error that says "Invalid time period",
check your START and END variables.

81
08:00:00,000 --> 08:06:00,000
Run echo for each. They should be in YYYY-MM-DD format.
If they're not, the date command might be different on your operating system.

82
08:06:00,000 --> 08:12:00,000
If you get an error that says "Access denied"
or "Unauthorized operation",

83
08:12:00,000 --> 08:18:00,000
your IAM user doesn't have permission to read Cost Explorer.
You need the AWSBillingReadOnlyAccess policy.

84
08:18:00,000 --> 08:24:00,000
Go back to Series one and add that policy to your user.

85
08:24:00,000 --> 08:30:00,000
If you get an empty response with no number,
your account might have zero spend. That's fine for testing.

86
08:30:00,000 --> 08:36:00,000
But if you're in production and you see zero,
something is wrong.

87
08:36:00,000 --> 08:42:00,000
Your credentials might be pointing to the wrong account.
Run get-caller-identity to see which account you're in.

88
08:42:00,000 --> 08:48:00,000
Now you're ready to find waste.

89
08:48:00,000 --> 08:54:00,000
The first command in any audit is total spend by service.
This is your opening slide.

90
08:54:00,000 --> 09:00:00,000
This is what you show your CTO.
This is the table that makes everything else make sense.

91
09:00:00,000 --> 09:06:00,000
Here is the command.

92
09:06:00,000 --> 09:12:00,000
aws ce get-cost-and-usage with time period Start END,
granularity MONTHLY, metrics BlendedCost,

93
09:12:00,000 --> 09:18:00,000
group-by type DIMENSION key SERVICE,
query results by time zero groups with blended cost amount greater than ten,

94
09:18:00,000 --> 09:24:00,000
output table.

95
09:24:00,000 --> 09:30:00,000
Run it. Paste it into your terminal. Hit enter.

96
09:30:00,000 --> 09:36:00,000
Let me explain what you're running.
Understanding is more important than copying.

97
09:36:00,000 --> 09:42:00,000
Time period uses your START and END variables.
START is thirty days ago. END is today.

98
09:42:00,000 --> 09:48:00,000
You're looking at the last thirty days of spend.
Thirty days is the standard for monthly reporting.

99
09:48:00,000 --> 09:54:00,000
It matches your AWS bill. It matches your finance team's expectations.

100
09:54:00,000 --> 10:00:00,000
Granularity is MONTHLY.
This tells Cost Explorer to give you one number per month.

101
10:00:00,000 --> 10:06:00,000
One row for EC2. One row for EKS.
One row for RDS. One row for S3.
One row for NAT Gateway. Clean and simple.

102
10:06:00,000 --> 10:12:00,000
Metrics use BlendedCost. This is important.
AWS has two cost metrics. Blended cost and unblended cost.

103
10:12:00,000 --> 10:18:00,000
Unblended cost is the list price. The sticker price.
The price before any discounts. It's what AWS publishes on their website.

104
10:18:00,000 --> 10:24:00,000
But almost no one pays that.
Most startups have discounts. Most use Savings Plans.

105
10:24:00,000 --> 10:30:00,000
Most use Reserved Instances. So unblended cost is misleading.

106
10:30:00,000 --> 10:36:00,000
Blended cost is what you actually pay after all discounts.

107
10:36:00,000 --> 10:42:00,000
After Savings Plans. After Reserved Instances.
After volume discounts. It's the real number.

108
10:42:00,000 --> 10:48:00,000
The number that actually hits your bank account.
Always use blended cost.

109
10:48:00,000 --> 10:54:00,000
Group by service is the magic.
This transforms a confusing bill into a clear table.

110
10:54:00,000 --> 11:00:00,000
EC2 gets its own row. EKS gets its own row.
RDS gets its own row. S3 gets its own row.

111
11:00:00,000 --> 11:06:00,000
Every service gets its own row.

112
11:06:00,000 --> 11:12:00,000
The query filters out any service that costs less than ten dollars.

113
11:12:00,000 --> 11:18:00,000
That removes all the tiny charges.
The fifty cents for Route53 health checks.

114
11:18:00,000 --> 11:24:00,000
The two dollars for CloudWatch logs.
You don't need those on your opening slide. They're noise.

115
11:24:00,000 --> 11:30:00,000
Now look at your output.

116
11:30:00,000 --> 11:36:00,000
The top row is almost always EC2.
Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud. That's your virtual machines.

117
11:36:00,000 --> 11:42:00,000
Your compute. Your servers. This is where most of your money goes.

118
11:42:00,000 --> 11:48:00,000
That's normal. That's expected. Compute is expensive.
Compute is what does the work.

119
11:48:00,000 --> 11:54:00,000
Now look at the second, third, and fourth rows.
This is where you find your opportunities.

120
11:54:00,000 --> 12:00:00,000
Let me give you a real-world interpretation guide.

121
12:00:00,000 --> 12:06:00,000
If NAT Gateway is in your top five, that's a red flag.
NAT Gateway is expensive.

122
12:06:00,000 --> 12:12:00,000
It means you're sending a lot of traffic through NAT Gateway.
Some of that traffic might be to S3 or DynamoDB.

123
12:12:00,000 --> 12:18:00,000
And all of that traffic could be free through VPC Endpoints.

124
12:18:00,000 --> 12:24:00,000
If EKS is high and you have multiple clusters,
that's waste. Each EKS cluster costs seventy-three dollars per month.

125
12:24:00,000 --> 12:30:00,000
If you have three clusters, that's two hundred nineteen dollars.
If you have five, that's three hundred sixty-five dollars.

126
12:30:00,000 --> 12:36:00,000
Could you consolidate development and staging into one cluster?
Could you use namespaces to separate environments instead of separate clusters?

127
12:36:00,000 --> 12:42:00,000
If RDS is in your top three, you have databases.
The biggest waste in RDS is development databases running twenty-four seven.

128
12:42:00,000 --> 12:48:00,000
No one uses them at three in the morning.
No one uses them on weekends.
But they're running. They're costing money.

129
12:48:00,000 --> 12:54:00,000
You can add stop and start schedules. That's sixty percent savings.

130
12:54:00,000 --> 13:00:00,000
If S3 is in your top five, S3 is cheap.
Two point three cents per gigabyte.

131
13:00:00,000 --> 13:06:00,000
But cheap times a lot is still expensive.
If you have one hundred terabytes in S3, that's two thousand three hundred dollars a month.

132
13:06:00,000 --> 13:12:00,000
Do you need all of it in standard storage?
Could some of it be in cheaper tiers?

133
13:12:00,000 --> 13:18:00,000
Do you have lifecycle policies to move old data automatically?

134
13:18:00,000 --> 13:24:00,000
Write down your top five services.
These are your optimization targets.

135
13:24:00,000 --> 13:30:00,000
Now save this to your baseline document.
You created this document in Series one. Now add to it.

136
13:30:00,000 --> 13:36:00,000
echo three equals signs SERIES 2 WASTE AUDIT three equals signs
with date.

137
13:36:00,000 --> 13:42:00,000
Then echo three equals signs SPEND BY SERVICE three equals signs.
Then run the same cost command and append the output to your baseline file.

138
13:42:00,000 --> 13:48:00,000
Now let's look at daily cost trends.
This finds anomalies, spikes, drops, and patterns.

139
13:48:00,000 --> 13:54:00,000
Things that don't look right.

140
13:54:00,000 --> 14:00:00,000
Run the same cost command but change granularity to DAILY.

141
14:00:00,000 --> 14:06:00,000
aws ce get-cost-and-usage with time period Start END,
granularity DAILY, metrics BlendedCost,

142
14:06:00,000 --> 14:12:00,000
query results by time zero start and blended cost amount,
output table.

143
14:12:00,000 --> 14:18:00,000
You'll see thirty rows, one for each day.
Each row has a date and a cost.

144
14:18:00,000 --> 14:24:00,000
Now look for patterns.

145
14:24:00,000 --> 14:30:00,000
Do you see a spike on a particular day?
Each spike is a story. What happened that day?

146
14:30:00,000 --> 14:36:00,000
Did you deploy a new service?
Did a batch job run longer than expected?

147
14:36:00,000 --> 14:42:00,000
Did a misconfigured auto-scaler spin up too many instances?

148
14:42:00,000 --> 14:48:00,000
Do you see a drop on weekends?
That's good. That means your workloads follow business hours.

149
14:48:00,000 --> 14:54:00,000
That means you have opportunities to scale down on weekends.

150
14:54:00,000 --> 15:00:00,000
If you see no drop on weekends, your workloads run twenty-four seven.
Ask yourself if they need to.

151
15:00:00,000 --> 15:06:00,000
Do you see a gradual increase over time?
That's natural. Workloads grow.

152
15:06:00,000 --> 15:12:00,000
But is the increase proportional to business growth?
If your cost goes up ten percent per month but revenue goes up five percent,
that's a problem.

153
15:12:00,000 --> 15:18:00,000
Do you see a sudden step up that never goes back down?
Something changed on that day and never changed back.

154
15:18:00,000 --> 15:24:00,000
What was it? A new service? Larger instance sizes?
A feature left on?

155
15:24:00,000 --> 15:30:00,000
Investigate the spikes. Look at the date.
Look at your deployment logs. Look at CloudTrail events.

156
15:30:00,000 --> 15:36:00,000
Ask your team what changed.
You'll often find something obvious.

157
15:36:00,000 --> 15:42:00,000
A test left running. A debug flag left enabled.
A load test that wasn't cleaned up.

158
15:42:00,000 --> 15:48:00,000
Now let's look at cost by region.
This finds resources running in regions you don't use.

159
15:48:00,000 --> 15:54:00,000
Run the cost command again. Group by region instead of service.
Query for all groups. Output as a table.

160
15:54:00,000 --> 16:00:00,000
You'll see a table of regions and costs.

161
16:00:00,000 --> 16:06:00,000
If your primary region is us-east-1, Northern Virginia,
you should see most of your cost there. That's your home.

162
16:06:00,000 --> 16:12:00,000
If you see significant cost in us-west-2, Oregon,
someone created resources on the west coast. Why?

163
16:12:00,000 --> 16:18:00,000
Maybe they were testing latency. Maybe they wanted disaster recovery.
Maybe they misconfigured Terraform.

164
16:18:00,000 --> 16:24:00,000
Maybe a developer spun up resources for a demo
and forgot to tear them down.

165
16:24:00,000 --> 16:30:00,000
If you see cost in eu-west-1, Ireland,
someone created resources in Europe. Why?

166
16:30:00,000 --> 16:36:00,000
Maybe you have European customers. Maybe you need GDPR compliance.
Investigate.

167
16:36:00,000 --> 16:42:00,000
If you see cost in a region you don't recognize,
like Sao Paulo, Bahrain, or Cape Town, definitely investigate.

168
16:42:00,000 --> 16:48:00,000
Those regions are usually not the default.
Someone intentionally chose them.

169
16:48:00,000 --> 16:54:00,000
Now find the actual resources.

170
16:54:00,000 --> 17:00:00,000
Loop through each region.
For each region, describe EC2 instances.

171
17:00:00,000 --> 17:06:00,000
for region in us-west-1 us-west-2 eu-west-1,
do echo checking region, then aws ec2 describe-instances.

172
17:06:00,000 --> 17:12:00,000
If you see any IDs, you have instances in that region.

173
17:12:00,000 --> 17:18:00,000
Then describe volumes in each region.
Then describe RDS instances. Then list S3 buckets.

174
17:18:00,000 --> 17:24:00,000
S3 is global, but you can see which region each bucket is in.
For any bucket you don't recognize, get its location.

175
17:24:00,000 --> 17:30:00,000
Once you find stray resources, you have three options.

176
17:30:00,000 --> 17:36:00,000
Option one: migrate them to your primary region.
This is work, but worth it if the resource is important.

177
17:36:00,000 --> 17:42:00,000
Option two: delete them.
If the resource is not important, just terminate, delete, and remove.

178
17:42:00,000 --> 17:48:00,000
Option three: tag them and add them to your regular reporting.
If the resource is supposed to be in that region, tag it with the region name.

179
17:48:00,000 --> 17:54:00,000
Then include it in your regular cost reporting.
But don't ignore it. Tag it. Track it. Own it.

180
17:54:00,000 --> 18:00:00,000
Now save cost by region to your baseline document.
Echo a header, run the command, and append the output.

181
18:00:00,000 --> 18:06:00,000
Now let's talk about cost anomaly detection.
This saves you from surprise bills.

182
18:06:00,000 --> 18:12:00,000
You enable it once. It runs forever.
It watches your spend. It learns your patterns.

183
18:12:00,000 --> 18:18:00,000
And it alerts you when something unexpected happens.
Before you see it on the bill.

184
18:18:00,000 --> 18:24:00,000
First, create an anomaly monitor.
Use create-anomaly-monitor.

185
18:24:00,000 --> 18:30:00,000
Give it a name like finops-monitor.
Set the type to DIMENSIONAL. Set the dimension to SERVICE.

186
18:30:00,000 --> 18:36:00,000
This monitor watches for anomalies by service.
It looks at EC2 spend, EKS spend, RDS spend, S3 spend, and NAT Gateway spend.

187
18:36:00,000 --> 18:42:00,000
If any service deviates from its historical pattern,
the monitor detects it.

188
18:42:00,000 --> 18:48:00,000
If EC2 spend doubles in a day, you'll know.
If NAT Gateway spend triples in a week, you'll know.

189
18:48:00,000 --> 18:54:00,000
If a new service appears, you'll know.

190
18:54:00,000 --> 19:00:00,000
Now get the monitor ARN.
You need this to create a subscription.

191
19:00:00,000 --> 19:06:00,000
Use get-anomaly-monitors and query for the ARN.
MONITOR_ARN equals that output.

192
19:06:00,000 --> 19:12:00,000
Now create an anomaly subscription.
Use create-anomaly-subscription.

193
19:12:00,000 --> 19:18:00,000
Give it a name like finops-alerts.
Provide the monitor ARN in a list.

194
19:18:00,000 --> 19:24:00,000
Add a subscriber with your email address.
Set the threshold to fifty dollars. Set frequency to DAILY.

195
19:24:00,000 --> 19:30:00,000
The threshold is the minimum anomaly impact to trigger an alert.
Fifty means any anomaly that changes your spend by fifty dollars or more
triggers an alert.

196
19:30:00,000 --> 19:36:00,000
You can set this lower for small anomalies
or higher to avoid noise.

197
19:36:00,000 --> 19:42:00,000
Frequency DAILY means you get a summary once per day.
You can also use IMMEDIATE for real-time alerts.

198
19:42:00,000 --> 19:48:00,000
Now check for existing anomalies from the last seven days.

199
19:48:00,000 --> 19:54:00,000
Use get-anomalies with date interval from seven days ago to today.
Query for the service and total impact.

200
19:54:00,000 --> 20:00:00,000
Run this command. Are there any anomalies?
If yes, investigate. What caused the spike?

201
20:00:00,000 --> 20:06:00,000
Was it expected? A deployment? A load test? A misconfiguration?

202
20:06:00,000 --> 20:12:00,000
Should you adjust your monitoring to ignore that kind of spike
in the future?

203
20:12:00,000 --> 20:18:00,000
Now let's talk about the easiest win in the entire audit.
Gp2 to gp3 migration.

204
20:18:00,000 --> 20:24:00,000
Twenty percent savings. Zero downtime. One command.
Same baseline performance.

205
20:24:00,000 --> 20:30:00,000
Let me explain the difference.

206
20:30:00,000 --> 20:36:00,000
Gp2 is the older generation of general purpose SSD volumes.
It costs ten cents per gigabyte per month.

207
20:36:00,000 --> 20:42:00,000
It provides a baseline of three IOPS per gigabyte.
A one hundred gigabyte volume gets three hundred IOPS baseline.

208
20:42:00,000 --> 20:48:00,000
It can burst to three thousand IOPS, but bursting is limited.

209
20:48:00,000 --> 20:54:00,000
Gp3 is the newer generation.
It costs eight cents per gigabyte per month. Twenty percent cheaper.

210
20:54:00,000 --> 21:00:00,000
It provides a baseline of three thousand IOPS regardless of size.
Even a one gigabyte volume gets three thousand IOPS.

211
21:00:00,000 --> 21:06:00,000
It also provides one hundred twenty-five megabytes per second
of throughput baseline. Gp2 doesn't have a throughput baseline.

212
21:06:00,000 --> 21:12:00,000
Gp3 is cheaper, faster, and more consistent.
There is no reason to use gp2 anymore.

213
21:12:00,000 --> 21:18:00,000
Every gp2 volume should be migrated.

214
21:18:00,000 --> 21:24:00,000
Here's how to find all your gp2 volumes.

215
21:24:00,000 --> 21:30:00,000
aws ec2 describe-volumes with filter volume-type gp2.
Query volume ID, size, state, and name tag. Output as a table.

216
21:30:00,000 --> 21:36:00,000
How many volumes do you see?
Each one is a candidate for migration.

217
21:36:00,000 --> 21:42:00,000
Now calculate potential savings.

218
21:42:00,000 --> 21:48:00,000
A one hundred gigabyte gp2 volume costs ten dollars per month.
Gp3 costs eight dollars. Savings of two dollars per month.

219
21:48:00,000 --> 21:54:00,000
A one terabyte volume saves twenty dollars per month.
Ten terabytes saves two hundred dollars per month.

220
21:54:00,000 --> 22:00:00,000
Now migrate a single volume to gp3.

221
22:00:00,000 --> 22:06:00,000
Use modify-volume. Provide the volume ID.
Set volume type to gp3. Set IOPS to three thousand.

222
22:06:00,000 --> 22:12:00,000
Set throughput to one hundred twenty-five.

223
22:12:00,000 --> 22:18:00,000
Replace the volume ID with your actual ID.
Three thousand IOPS is the baseline. You can go higher if needed,
but higher costs more.

224
22:18:00,000 --> 22:24:00,000
One hundred twenty-five throughput is the baseline.

225
22:24:00,000 --> 22:30:00,000
Now monitor the migration progress.
Use describe-volumes-modifications.

226
22:30:00,000 --> 22:36:00,000
Query for volume ID, modification state, target volume type, and progress.

227
22:36:00,000 --> 22:42:00,000
The modification state can be modifying, optimizing, or completed.

228
22:42:00,000 --> 22:48:00,000
Modifying means the change is in progress.
The volume is usable during this time.

229
22:48:00,000 --> 22:54:00,000
Performance might be reduced, but it works.

230
22:54:00,000 --> 23:00:00,000
Optimizing means the modification is complete
but performance is still improving. This can take hours.

231
23:00:00,000 --> 23:06:00,000
Completed means the modification is fully complete.
The volume is now gp3. Performance is at the target level.

232
23:06:00,000 --> 23:12:00,000
The whole process takes between one and forty-eight hours.
You don't need to wait. The volume is usable during migration.

233
23:12:00,000 --> 23:18:00,000
Now migrate all gp2 volumes at once.

234
23:18:00,000 --> 23:24:00,000
Find every gp2 volume ID.
Loop through each ID. For each volume, run the modify-volume command.

235
23:24:00,000 --> 23:30:00,000
One command. Zero downtime. Twenty percent savings.

236
23:30:00,000 --> 23:36:00,000
Now let's find unattached Elastic IPs.
These are pure waste. Each one costs three dollars and sixty-five cents per month.

237
23:36:00,000 --> 23:42:00,000
Doing nothing. Just sitting there.

238
23:42:00,000 --> 23:48:00,000
What is an Elastic IP? It's a static public IP address
you can allocate to your AWS account.

239
23:48:00,000 --> 23:54:00,000
You can attach it to an EC2 instance, a NAT Gateway, or a load balancer.
When attached, it's useful. When not attached, it's waste.

240
23:54:00,000 --> 00:00:00,000
AWS charges for unattached Elastic IPs
because they're scarce resources.

241
00:00:00,000 --> 00:06:00,000
There are a limited number of public IP addresses.
If you're hoarding them, AWS wants you to either use them or release them.

242
00:06:00,000 --> 00:12:00,000
Here's how to find unattached Elastic IPs.
Describe addresses. Query for addresses with no association ID.

243
00:12:00,000 --> 00:18:00,000
Show allocation ID, public IP, and domain. Output as a table.

244
00:18:00,000 --> 00:24:00,000
The query filters for addresses that have no AssociationId.
AssociationId is set when the EIP is attached to something.

245
00:24:00,000 --> 00:30:00,000
If there's no AssociationId, the EIP is unattached.

246
00:30:00,000 --> 00:36:00,000
How many rows do you see?
Each row is an unattached EIP.

247
00:36:00,000 --> 00:42:00,000
Each one costs three dollars and sixty-five cents a month.
For five EIPs, that's eighteen dollars a month.

248
00:42:00,000 --> 00:48:00,000
For ten, thirty-six dollars. For twenty, seventy-three dollars.

249
00:48:00,000 --> 00:54:00,000
Now release them.
Find every unattached EIP allocation ID.

250
00:54:00,000 --> 01:00:00,000
Loop through each ID. For each ID, run release-address.
The address goes back to the AWS pool. You stop paying for it.

251
01:00:00,000 --> 01:06:00,000
Now let's find stopped instances.
Stopped instances don't charge for compute.

252
01:06:00,000 --> 01:12:00,000
But their EBS volumes still do.
A stopped instance with a one hundred gigabyte gp3 volume costs eight dollars per month.

253
01:12:00,000 --> 01:18:00,000
Even though it's doing nothing. Even though it's not running.

254
01:18:00,000 --> 01:24:00,000
Why would you stop an instance instead of terminating it?
Maybe you want to preserve the data.

255
01:24:00,000 --> 01:30:00,000
Maybe you want to keep the configuration.
Maybe you're not sure if you'll need it again.

256
01:30:00,000 --> 01:36:00,000
But if an instance has been stopped for more than seven days,
you probably don't need it.

257
01:36:00,000 --> 01:42:00,000
If it's been stopped for more than thirty days,
you definitely don't need it.

258
01:42:00,000 --> 01:48:00,000
If it's been stopped for more than ninety days,
you should have terminated it already.

259
01:48:00,000 --> 01:54:00,000
Here's how to find stopped instances.
Describe instances. Filter for state name stopped.

260
01:54:00,000 --> 02:00:00,000
Query for instance ID, type, and name tag. Output as a table.

261
02:00:00,000 --> 02:06:00,000
How many stopped instances do you see?
Each one is a candidate for termination.

262
02:06:00,000 --> 02:12:00,000
For each stopped instance, ask these questions.

263
02:12:00,000 --> 02:18:00,000
Why is it stopped? Was it intentional? By a script?
Because it failed?

264
02:18:00,000 --> 02:24:00,000
When was it stopped? Check the state transition reason field.
If it was stopped more than thirty days ago, terminate it.

265
02:24:00,000 --> 02:30:00,000
Who stopped it? Check CloudTrail.
Who ran the stop instances API call? Can you ask them why?

266
02:30:00,000 --> 02:36:00,000
Does anyone need it? Send an email to the team.
Give them a deadline. If no one responds, terminate it.

267
02:36:00,000 --> 02:42:00,000
If the instance has important data, snapshot the volumes first.
Use create-snapshot with a description that includes the date.

268
02:42:00,000 --> 02:48:00,000
Then terminate the instance with terminate-instances.

269
02:48:00,000 --> 02:54:00,000
Now let's find unattached EBS volumes.
These are volumes not attached to any instance.

270
02:54:00,000 --> 03:00:00,000
Just sitting there. Costing money. Doing nothing.

271
03:00:00,000 --> 03:06:00,000
Why would you have an unattached volume?
Maybe you detached it from an instance and forgot to delete it.

272
03:06:00,000 --> 03:12:00,000
Maybe you created a volume from a snapshot but never attached it.
Maybe a script created a volume and failed to attach it.

273
03:12:00,000 --> 03:18:00,000
Here's how to find unattached volumes.
Describe volumes. Filter for status available.

274
03:18:00,000 --> 03:24:00,000
Query for volume ID, size, type, and creation time.
Output as a table.

275
03:24:00,000 --> 03:30:00,000
Status available means the volume is not attached to any instance.
It's available to be attached, but it's not.

276
03:30:00,000 --> 03:36:00,000
How many unattached volumes do you see?
Each one costs money.

277
03:36:00,000 --> 03:42:00,000
A one hundred gigabyte gp3 volume costs eight dollars a month.
A one terabyte volume costs eighty dollars.

278
03:42:00,000 --> 03:48:00,000
Ten volumes cost eight hundred dollars.

279
03:48:00,000 --> 03:54:00,000
Ask the same questions. Why is it unattached?
When was it created? Who created it?

280
03:54:00,000 --> 04:00:00,000
Does anyone need it? Can you delete it?

281
04:00:00,000 --> 04:06:00,000
If you're not sure, snapshot it first.
Here's a bulk snapshot and delete script.

282
04:06:00,000 --> 04:12:00,000
Find every unattached volume ID.
Loop through each ID. Create a snapshot with a description that includes the date.

283
04:12:00,000 --> 04:18:00,000
The delete command is commented out for safety.
Run the script first to create snapshots.

284
04:18:00,000 --> 04:24:00,000
Review them. Make sure you don't need them.
Then uncomment the delete command and run again.

285
04:24:00,000 --> 04:30:00,000
Now let's find old snapshots.
Snapshots older than ninety days with no deletion policy.

286
04:30:00,000 --> 04:36:00,000
Each snapshot costs money.
Old snapshots that are no longer needed are waste.

287
04:36:00,000 --> 04:42:00,000
Why would you have old snapshots?
Maybe you created them for backup and forgot to set a retention policy.

288
04:42:00,000 --> 04:48:00,000
Maybe you created them before a migration and never cleaned up.
Maybe a script created them and never deleted them.

289
04:48:00,000 --> 04:54:00,000
Here's how to find old snapshots.
Describe snapshots for your account ID.

290
04:54:00,000 --> 05:00:00,000
Query for snapshots created more than ninety days ago.
Show snapshot ID, date, and size. Output as a table.

291
05:00:00,000 --> 05:06:00,000
How many old snapshots do you see?
Each one is a candidate for deletion.

292
05:06:00,000 --> 05:12:00,000
For each old snapshot, ask these questions.
Why was it created? When? Does anyone need it? Can you delete it?

293
05:12:00,000 --> 05:18:00,000
Check the snapshot description.
Many snapshots are created automatically by backup tools.

294
05:18:00,000 --> 05:24:00,000
Those tools usually have deletion policies.
If a snapshot has no deletion policy, it's probably orphaned.

295
05:24:00,000 --> 05:30:00,000
Now let's talk about NAT Gateway.
This is the silent killer.

296
05:30:00,000 --> 05:36:00,000
NAT Gateway is expensive.
And most of the traffic going through it doesn't need to.

297
05:36:00,000 --> 05:42:00,000
First, see how much you're spending on NAT Gateway.

298
05:42:00,000 --> 05:48:00,000
Run the cost command. Filter for usage type group EC2 colon NAT Gateway.
Query for the amount.

299
05:48:00,000 --> 05:54:00,000
How much are you spending?
For a moderately busy cluster, it's often hundreds of dollars a month.

300
05:54:00,000 --> 06:00:00,000
For a busy cluster, it can be thousands.

301
06:00:00,000 --> 06:06:00,000
Now let's fix it.

302
06:06:00,000 --> 06:12:00,000
The problem is that most startups send all their traffic
through NAT Gateway.

303
06:12:00,000 --> 06:18:00,000
Including traffic to S3 and DynamoDB.
S3 and DynamoDB traffic through NAT Gateway costs four point five cents per gigabyte.

304
06:18:00,000 --> 06:24:00,000
But through VPC Endpoints, it's completely free.

305
06:24:00,000 --> 06:30:00,000
VPC Endpoints are free.
No hourly charge. No data transfer charge. Completely free.

306
06:30:00,000 --> 06:36:00,000
Why doesn't everyone use them?
Because most people don't know they exist.

307
06:36:00,000 --> 06:42:00,000
Or they think they're complicated or expensive.
They're not. They're free and easy.

308
06:42:00,000 --> 06:48:00,000
Here's how to create a VPC Endpoint for S3.

309
06:48:00,000 --> 06:54:00,000
First, get your VPC ID.
Describe VPCs. Filter for non-default VPCs. Query for the first VPC ID.

310
06:54:00,000 --> 07:00:00,000
Second, get your route table IDs.
Describe route tables. Filter for your VPC ID. Query for route table IDs.

311
07:00:00,000 --> 07:06:00,000
Third, create the VPC Endpoint for S3.
Use create-vpc-endpoint.

312
07:06:00,000 --> 07:12:00,000
Provide your VPC ID. Provide the service name for S3 in your region.
Provide the route table IDs. Set the type to gateway.

313
07:12:00,000 --> 07:18:00,000
That's it. Now all S3 traffic from your VPC
goes through the free endpoint instead of the expensive NAT Gateway.

314
07:18:00,000 --> 07:24:00,000
Now do the same for DynamoDB.
Use the same command with the DynamoDB service name.

315
07:24:00,000 --> 07:30:00,000
Now S3 and DynamoDB traffic is free.
Your NAT Gateway bill will drop immediately.

316
07:30:00,000 --> 07:36:00,000
For other services like ECR, Secrets Manager, and CloudWatch,
you need interface endpoints.

317
07:36:00,000 --> 07:42:00,000
Interface endpoints cost one cent per hour per Availability Zone.
That's seven dollars and twenty cents per month per zone.

318
07:42:00,000 --> 07:48:00,000
For three zones, that's twenty-one dollars and sixty cents per month.

319
07:48:00,000 --> 07:54:00,000
If you're spending more than that on NAT Gateway traffic
to those services, the interface endpoint saves you money.

320
07:54:00,000 --> 08:00:00,000
The break-even point is about three hundred gigabytes per month.

321
08:00:00,000 --> 08:06:00,000
Now let's find idle load balancers.
Load balancers with no healthy targets.

322
08:06:00,000 --> 08:12:00,000
They're running. They're costing money.
But they're not serving traffic.

323
08:12:00,000 --> 08:18:00,000
First, list all load balancers.
Describe load balancers. Query for ARN, name, type, and state.

324
08:18:00,000 --> 08:24:00,000
For each load balancer, check its target groups.
Describe target groups. Query for target group ARN and load balancer ARN.

325
08:24:00,000 --> 08:30:00,000
Then for each target group, describe target health.
Count how many targets are healthy.

326
08:30:00,000 --> 08:36:00,000
If a load balancer has zero healthy targets, it's idle.
Delete it. Or fix the target group. But don't leave it running.

327
08:36:00,000 --> 08:42:00,000
Now let's put it all together.
Here's a complete waste audit summary script.

328
08:42:00,000 --> 08:48:00,000
Echo a header. Then get the count of gp2 volumes.
Estimate monthly savings assuming one hundred gigabytes average.

329
08:48:00,000 --> 08:54:00,000
Get the count of unattached EIPs.
Estimate savings at three dollars sixty-five cents each.

330
08:54:00,000 --> 09:00:00,000
Get the count of stopped instances.
Estimate savings assuming one hundred gigabyte EBS each.

331
09:00:00,000 --> 09:06:00,000
Get the count of unattached volumes.
Estimate savings assuming one hundred gigabytes each.

332
09:06:00,000 --> 09:12:00,000
Get the NAT Gateway cost.
Estimate savings after VPC endpoints at fifty to one hundred percent.

333
09:12:00,000 --> 09:18:00,000
Run this script. Write down the numbers.
These are your identified savings.

334
09:18:00,000 --> 09:24:00,000
This is what you've found just by running the commands
in Series two.

335
09:24:00,000 --> 09:30:00,000
Now save everything to your baseline document.
Echo each finding with its count or cost.

336
09:30:00,000 --> 09:36:00,000
Let's recap what you've built in Series two.

337
09:36:00,000 --> 09:42:00,000
You ran your first real cost discovery commands.
Total spend by service. Daily cost trends. Cost by region.

338
09:42:00,000 --> 09:48:00,000
You identified your top five cost drivers.
You know where to focus your optimization efforts.

339
09:48:00,000 --> 09:54:00,000
You enabled cost anomaly detection.
You created a monitor that watches for unexpected spend.

340
09:54:00,000 --> 10:00:00,000
You created a subscription that alerts you when anomalies are detected.
You'll never be surprised by a bill again.

341
10:00:00,000 --> 10:06:00,000
You found every gp2 volume in your account.
You migrated them to gp3. Twenty percent savings. Zero downtime. One command.

342
10:06:00,000 --> 10:12:00,000
You found every unattached Elastic IP.
You released them. No more three dollar sixty-five cent paperweights.

343
10:12:00,000 --> 10:18:00,000
You found stopped instances still paying for EBS volumes.
You snapshotted and terminated them.

344
10:18:00,000 --> 10:24:00,000
You found unattached EBS volumes.
You snapshotted and deleted them.

345
10:24:00,000 --> 10:30:00,000
You found old snapshots.
You reviewed and deleted the ones you didn't need.

346
10:30:00,000 --> 10:36:00,000
You analyzed your NAT Gateway cost.
You created VPC Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB.

347
10:36:00,000 --> 10:42:00,000
Free traffic instead of expensive traffic.

348
10:42:00,000 --> 10:48:00,000
You found idle load balancers.
You deleted the ones with no healthy targets.

349
10:48:00,000 --> 10:54:00,000
By the end of Series two, you have identified
actual dollar amounts of waste in your AWS account.

350
10:54:00,000 --> 11:00:00,000
Not estimated. Not projected. Not theoretical.
Actual waste from your account, your resources, your bill.

351
11:00:00,000 --> 11:06:00,000
And you have a plan to eliminate every dollar.

352
11:06:00,000 --> 11:12:00,000
Here's what you need before Series three.

353
11:12:00,000 --> 11:18:00,000
First, your baseline document must be updated
with the waste audit findings.

354
11:18:00,000 --> 11:24:00,000
Run cat on your baseline file to verify.
You should see the waste audit findings at the bottom.

355
11:24:00,000 --> 11:30:00,000
Second, you should have migrated at least one gp2 volume to gp3.
Run describe-volumes-modifications to check the status.

356
11:30:00,000 --> 11:36:00,000
The modification state should be completed or optimizing.

357
11:36:00,000 --> 11:42:00,000
Third, you should have released at least one unattached EIP.
Run describe-addresses to verify. You should see fewer addresses than before.

358
11:42:00,000 --> 11:48:00,000
Fourth, you should have created VPC Endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB.
Run describe-vpc-endpoints to verify.

359
11:48:00,000 --> 11:54:00,000
You should see endpoints for S3 and DynamoDB with state available.

360
11:54:00,000 --> 12:00:00,000
If you have all four, you're ready for Series three.

361
12:00:00,000 --> 12:06:00,000
In Series three, we deploy Kubecost on EKS.
We get cost visibility at the namespace level.

362
12:06:00,000 --> 12:12:00,000
We see exactly which team is spending what.
We see efficiency scores. We see idle CPU and memory costs.

363
12:12:00,000 --> 12:18:00,000
We stop guessing. We start knowing.

364
12:18:00,000 --> 12:24:00,000
Let's go to Series three.

